PAPER 1

This section aims to replicate Figure 2 from the paper “Irrigation Dams, Water, and Infant Mortality: Evidence from South Africa”.

Load spatial datasets (district boundaries, elevation data, and dam locations). Compute river gradients (slope) using elevation data. Extract average slope per district to understand the variation in river gradients. Plot a map with dams and river gradients using ggplot2.

{r}
# Required packages 
install.packages(c("sf", "terra", "ggplot2", "dplyr", "exactextractr", "readxl"))
# The necessary libraries
library(sf)       
library(terra)    
library(ggplot2)  
library(dplyr)    
library(exactextractr) 
library(readxl)

We will load:

  • District boundaries (Shapefile): Defines municipal districts.

  • Topography data (Raster): Elevation data for South Africa.

  • Dam locations (Excel): Contains latitudes and longitudes of dams.

{r}
# the district boundaries (vector data)
districts_sf <- st_read("/Users/sanskriti/Desktop/PLOT1/MDB_Local_Municipal_Boundary_2018.shp")

# elevation data (raster data)
topography_sf <- rast("/Users/sanskriti/Desktop/PLOT1/South African topography.tif")

# dam location data 
dams_data <- read_excel("/Users/sanskriti/Desktop/Africa-dams_eng.xlsx", sheet = "Dams")
# Filter the dataset to only include dams in South Africa
sa_dams <- dams_data[dams_data$Country == "South Africa", ]

The river gradient determines how steep or flat a river flows.We calculate slope from the elevation raster using the terrain() function. terrain(raster, v = "slope", unit = "degrees"): Computes the slope (gradient) from elevation data. The unit "degrees" ensures we get values in angle form.

{r}
library(terra)
print(topography_sf)
# Computing the slope in degrees
slope_raster <- terrain(topography_sf, v = "slope", unit = "degrees")

plot(slope_raster, main = "Slope Raster of South Africa")

Extract the mean slope per district:

Each district has multiple slopes within its boundaries. We need to compute the average slope per district to summarize this data meaningfully. exact_extract(raster, vector, "mean"): Computes the average slope for each district by overlaying the raster onto the vector.

{r}
# Extracting mean slope per district
districts_sf$avg_gradient <- exact_extract(slope_raster, districts_sf, "mean")
summary(districts_sf$avg_gradient)

Dam coordinates (latitude & longitude) are stored as text in the dataset. We must convert them into an sf (spatial) object for mapping. st_as_sf(): Converts a data frame into a spatial object with latitude & longitude.

{r}
# Ensuring longitude and latitude columns are numeric
sa_dams$Longitude <- as.numeric(sa_dams$'Decimal degree longitude')
sa_dams$Latitude <- as.numeric(sa_dams$'Decimal degree latitude')
sum(is.na(sa_dams$`Decimal degree longitude`)) 
sum(is.na(sa_dams$`Decimal degree latitude`))  

# Missing coordinates
sa_dams <- sa_dams[!is.na(sa_dams$`Decimal degree longitude`) & 
                     !is.na(sa_dams$`Decimal degree latitude`), ]

# Converting dam data into an sf object
dams_sf <- st_as_sf(sa_dams, coords = c("Decimal degree longitude", "Decimal degree latitude"), crs = 4326)
dams_sf <- dams_sf %>%
  mutate(longitude = st_coordinates(.)[,1],  
         latitude = st_coordinates(.)[,2])   

head(dams_sf)

To ensure all datasets align properly on the map, they must share the same coordinate system (CRS: EPSG 4326, WGS 84). st_transform(): Converts vector layers to EPSG 4326. project(): Converts raster layers to EPSG 4326.

{r}
install.packages("ggspatial") 
library(ggspatial)
# Transforming vector layers to match WGS 84 (EPSG:4326)
districts_sf <- st_transform(districts_sf, crs = 4326)
dams_sf <- st_transform(dams_sf, crs = 4326)

topography_sf <- project(topography_sf, "EPSG:4326")

Plot

Now, we visualize the district boundaries, river gradients, and dam locations using ggplot2.In the ggplot() code, we first plot the district boundaries using geom_sf(data = districts_sf, aes(fill = avg_gradient), color = "white", size = 0.2), which fills each district with a shade based on its average river gradient (avg_gradient) while outlining them in white. Then, we overlay dam locations as black dots with geom_sf(data = dams_sf, color = "black", size = 0.4, alpha = 0.7), . Next defining the map’s spatial extent using coord_sf(xlim = c(16, 33), ylim = c(-35, -21), expand = FALSE, datum = NA), ensuring proper centering on South Africa . The grayscale gradient is set with scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("white", "gray", "black"), name = "Avg. River Gradient", breaks = c(2.5, 5, 7.5, 10, 12.5)), where lighter shades represent flatter areas and darker ones indicate steeper slopes. Finally, labs() adds the title, subtitle, and data source, while theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "bottom", text = element_text(size = 14), panel.grid = element_blank()) .

{r}
library(ggplot2)
library(sf)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = districts_sf, aes(fill = avg_gradient), color = "white", size = 0.2) +
  
  geom_sf(data = dams_sf, color = "black", size = 0.4, alpha = 0.7) + 
  
  coord_sf(xlim = c(16, 33), ylim = c(-35, -21), expand = FALSE, datum = NA) +
  
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("white", "gray", "black"),
                       name = "Avg. River Gradient",
                       breaks = c(2.5, 5, 7.5, 10, 12.5)) +
  
  labs(title = "Dam Locations and Average River Gradient by District",
       subtitle = "HydroSHEDS and Africa Dams Data",
       caption = "Source: HydroSHEDS, Natural Earth") +
  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    text = element_text(size = 14),
    panel.grid = element_blank()  
  )

The population density raster is cropped to match the extent of the district boundaries using crop(). Then, mask() is applied to ensure that only areas within the district boundaries retain values, while areas outside the boundaries are masked out. To ensure all spatial datasets align correctly, they are transformed to a common coordinate reference system (CRS). The CRS of the district boundaries is retrieved using st_crs(districts), and the electricity grid and roads are then transformed to match this CRS using st_transform().

{r}
population_density <- mask(crop(population_density, districts), districts)
crs_target <- st_crs(districts)
electricity_grid <- st_transform(electricity_grid, crs_target)
roads <- st_transform(roads, crs_target)

Since raster data consists of continuous grid cells, it is converted into discrete points for spatial analysis. The rasterToPoints() function extracts values from the raster and stores them as individual points. The extracted points are then converted into an sf object for compatibility with spatial operations.

{r}
class(roads)
population_df <- as.data.frame(rasterToPoints(population_density))
primary_roads <- roads[roads$fclass == "secondary", ]


# Convert raster to points
population_points <- rasterToPoints(population_density, spatial = TRUE)
# Convert to sf object
population_sf <- st_as_sf(population_points)

To associate each population point with its corresponding district, a spatial join is performed using st_join(). This assigns district information to each population density point. The population density values are aggregated at the district level. The aggregated population density values are merged with the district boundaries dataset using left_join(), ensuring that each district now contains its corresponding population density value.

{r}
#  spatial join
population_joined <- st_join(population_sf, districts)
population_density_aggregated <- population_joined %>%
  group_by(shapeID) %>%
  summarize(mean_density = mean(eth_pd_2012_1km_ASCII_XYZ, na.rm = TRUE))
population_density_aggregated_df <- as.data.frame(population_density_aggregated)

districts_filled <- districts %>%
  left_join(population_density_aggregated_df, by = "shapeID")

# Convert population_df back to a raster object
population_raster <- rasterFromXYZ(population_df[, c("x", "y", "eth_pd_2012_1km_ASCII_XYZ")])

crs(population_raster) <- st_crs(districts)$proj4string

PAPER 3

This section aims to replicate Figure. 2: Population in Brazil’s meso-regions (or districts) in different periods from Pellegrina, H.S. and Sotelo, S., 2021. Migration, Specialization, and Trade: Evidence from Brazil’s March to the West.

The dataset of Brazil’s meso-regions is loaded using st_read(), ensuring the correct administrative divisions are available for mapping. The dataset is then grouped by meso-region using group_by(nomemeso), aggregating geometries with st_union(). Additionally, specific region names are corrected with mutate() to maintain consistency in naming conventions.

{r}
library(sf)
library(dplyr)
library(readxl)

gdf <- st_read("C:/Users/amarc/Downloads/microrregioes_e_mesorregioes_geograficas_1990/RG2017_micromeso89.shp")

gdf_grouped <- gdf %>%
  group_by(nomemeso) %>%
  summarise(
    UF = first(UF),  # Keeps the first UF encountered for each mesoregion
    geometry = st_union(geometry)  # Merges geometries
  )

# Renaming the specific values in the "nomemeso" column of gdf_grouped
gdf_grouped <- gdf_grouped %>%
  mutate(nomemeso = case_when(
    nomemeso == "Sul - Sudoeste de Minas" ~ "Sul/Sudoeste de Minas",
    nomemeso == "Triângulo Mineiro - Alto Paranaíba" ~ "Triângulo Mineiro/Alto Paranaíba",
    TRUE ~ nomemeso  
  ))

It is then merged with the spatial data using left_join() on the nomemeso column to associate population data with meso-regions. The North and Central-West regions are identified using their UF codes. These regions will later be highlighted in the visualization.

{r}
population_data <- read_excel("C:/Users/amarc/Downloads/ipeadata[28-01-2025-07-03].xls")

merged_data <- gdf_grouped %>%
  left_join(population_data, by = c("nomemeso" = "Meso-região"))
head(merged_data)

# Define the UF codes for North and Central-West regions
highlighted_uf_codes <- c(11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 50, 51, 52, 53)

Population data is normalized by dividing each year’s population by the total population in that year, creating a relative measure (pop_share). The population shares are classified into quantile-based bins to create meaningful population categories for mapping. This is done using cut() and quantile(). The North and Central-West regions are extracted and merged into a single boundary to highlight them in the final visualization.

{r}
years <- c("1950", "1980", "2010")

# Normalize population by total population per year
for (year in years) {
  merged_data[[paste0("pop_share_", year)]] <- merged_data[[year]] / sum(merged_data[[year]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

# Function to classify population shares into 5 equal-size bins using quantiles
classify_population <- function(year) {
  pop_column <- paste0("pop_share_", year)
  
  # quantile-based breaks ensuring 5 groups
  breaks <- quantile(merged_data[[pop_column]], probs = seq(0, 1, length.out = 6), na.rm = TRUE)
  
  
  labels <- paste0(round(breaks[-6], 3), " - ", round(breaks[-1], 3))  
  
  
  merged_data[[paste0("pop_class_", year)]] <<- cut(merged_data[[pop_column]], breaks = breaks, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = labels)
}

Plot

The ggplot() function is used to generate separate maps for 1950, 1980, and 2010. The meso-regions are colored according to their population share categories, while the North and Central-West boundaries are outlined in red.

{r}

library(ggplot2)
color_palette <- c("#D4E3F4", "#A1C1E6", "#4E8CCF", "#1660A7", "#08306B") 

# Create a separate dataset containing only the North and Central-West regions
highlighted_data <- merged_data %>% filter(UF %in% highlighted_uf_codes)

highlighted_boundary <- highlighted_data %>%
  summarise(geometry = st_union(geometry)) %>%  # Merge into a single polygon
  st_cast("MULTILINESTRING")  # Ensure it’s a single continuous border

# Function to create a population share map with only the **outer** border in red
create_map <- function(year) {
  ggplot() +
    
    # Mesoregion borders (grey)
    geom_sf(data = merged_data, aes(fill = get(paste0("pop_class_", year))), color = "grey50", size = 0.2) +
    
    # Highlighting region's **outer boundary only** (red)
    geom_sf(data = highlighted_boundary, color = "red", fill = NA, size = 1) +
    
    # Color scale for population share
    scale_fill_manual(values = color_palette, name = "Pop. Share", drop = FALSE) +
    
    theme_minimal() +
    ggtitle(paste("Population Distribution in", year))
}

# Generating maps for 1950, 1980, and 2010
map_1950 <- create_map("1950")
map_1980 <- create_map("1980")
map_2010 <- create_map("2010")

print(map_1950)
print(map_1980)
print(map_2010)

The capital names are joined with the Brazil state boundaries using left_join(). The st_make_valid() function ensures geometries are correctly processed. Centroids of states are computed using st_centroid(), which provides approximate locations of capitals.

{r}
library(dplyr)
library(sf)

# Join the capitals to the state geometries
brazil_with_capitals <- brazil %>%
  left_join(state_capitals, by = c("name" = "state"))
brazil_with_capitals <- brazil_with_capitals %>%
  mutate(geometry = st_make_valid(geometry))
capitals_sf <- brazil_with_capitals %>%
  filter(!is.na(capital)) %>%  # Keep only rows with valid capitals
  mutate(capital_coords = st_centroid(geometry)) %>%  # Calculate centroids
  st_as_sf()
capitals_sf <- capitals_sf %>%
  select(capital, capital_coords) %>%
  st_set_geometry("capital_coords")
plot(st_geometry(capitals_sf), main = "Brazilian State Capitals")

A graph is constructed from the state capitals’ coordinates using igraph. A minimum spanning tree (MST) is computed, which represents the shortest possible network connecting all capitals while minimizing total distance.

{r}
library(igraph)
capitals_coords <- st_coordinates(capitals_sf)

# Calculate distance matrix
distance_matrix <- as.matrix(dist(capitals_coords))

g <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(distance_matrix, weighted = TRUE, mode = "undirected")
mst <- mst(g)

# Extract MST edges
mst_edges <- as_data_frame(mst, what = "edges")
mst_edges$from <- as.integer(mst_edges$from)
mst_edges$to <- as.integer(mst_edges$to)

# Create spatial lines for the MST
lines_list <- lapply(1:nrow(mst_edges), function(i) {
  st_linestring(rbind(
    capitals_coords[mst_edges$from[i], ],
    capitals_coords[mst_edges$to[i], ]
  ))
})

# Convert MST to sf object
mst_sf <- st_sfc(lines_list, crs = st_crs(capitals_sf))
mst_sf <- st_sf(geometry = mst_sf)

The radial highways are identified by filtering highways within a 50 km buffer around Brasília, assuming these highways originate from the capital. Highways that do not pass through Brasília are classified as non-radial.

{r}
library(sf)
# Define Brasília's location (latitude and longitude)
brasilia_coords <- st_point(c(-47.9292, -15.7801))  
brasilia_buffer <- st_sfc(brasilia_coords, crs = st_crs(federal_highways)) %>%
  st_buffer(dist = 50000)  # 50 km buffer around Brasília

radial_highways <- federal_highways[st_intersects(federal_highways, brasilia_buffer, sparse = FALSE), ]
non_radial_highways <- federal_highways %>%
  filter(!(ds_local_i == "Brasília" | ds_local_f == "Brasília"))

All spatial datasets are transformed to the EPSG 4326 coordinate reference system to ensure compatibility in plotting.

non_radial_highways <- st_transform(non_radial_highways, 4326)

  geom_sf(data = mst_sf, color = "black", size = 0.6, linetype = "dotted") +
  
  geom_sf(data = capitals_sf, color = "black", size = 2) +
  
  geom_text(data = capitals_sf %>% st_drop_geometry(),
            aes(x = st_coordinates(capitals_sf)[, 1],
                y = st_coordinates(capitals_sf)[, 2],
                label = capital),
            size = 3, hjust = -0.2, vjust = -0.2) +
  
  labs(
    title = "Map of Brazil's Infrastructure",
    subtitle = "Minimum Spanning Tree, Highways, and Capitals",
    caption = "Source: IBGE and OpenStreetMap"
  ) +
  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    axis.title = element_blank()
  )
